Technical Stack & System Workflow Document
Project: Nexus-V
Architecture Style: Microservices (Node.js Core + Python AI/Vision Engine)

1. The Tech Stack
A. Frontend (User App & Partner Dashboard)
Framework: React.js (for the Partner Web Dashboard) and React Native (for the Mobile App). Hackathon Tip: If time is tight, build a responsive React.js Progressive Web App (PWA) for both to share components.

Styling: Tailwind CSS. Essential for rapidly building the "Precision Modernism" glassmorphism UI without writing endless custom CSS files.

3D/Visuals (Optional 'Wow' Factor): Three.js. You can use this to render a lightweight 3D interactive car model on the dashboard to show which part the mechanic is fixing.

State Management: Zustand or Redux Toolkit (Zustand is faster to set up for hackathons) to manage live queue states and EV slot timers globally.

B. Backend (The Real-Time Core)
Runtime & Framework: Node.js with Express.js. Fast, asynchronous, and perfect for handling thousands of rapid API calls.

Real-Time Engine: Socket.io. This is non-negotiable. It provides the bi-directional communication needed for the live queue counters and instant EV slot status changes.

Authentication: JSON Web Tokens (JWT). Keep it stateless and fast.

C. Microservice (The "Trust Engine")
Framework: Python with FastAPI (or Flask). FastAPI is incredibly fast and self-documents, which is great for hackathons.

Computer Vision: OpenCV. When a mechanic uploads a photo, this library quickly analyzes the image to ensure it isn't pitch-black, excessively blurry, or a duplicate, acting as your automated fraud-prevention layer.

D. Database & Storage
Database: MongoDB (with Mongoose ODM). Its document-based structure easily handles the varied data shapes of car washes, EV stations, and complex mechanic quotes.

Image Storage: Cloudinary or AWS S3. Hackathon Tip: Cloudinary is usually easier to set up in 10 minutes and gives you free image optimization URLs.

E. Deployment (Hackathon Ready)
Frontend: Vercel (Instant deployments from GitHub).

Node Backend: Render or Railway (Easy WebSockets support).

Python Microservice: Render (Deploys FastAPI seamlessly).

Database: MongoDB Atlas (Free cloud cluster).

2. The Full System Workflow (How Data Moves)
Here is the exact lifecycle of the two most critical actions in your app.

Workflow A: The "Trust Layer" (Mechanic Uploads Proof)
This flow proves to the judges that your app stops fraud in real-time.

Trigger: Mechanic takes a photo of worn brake pads and enters a ₹5,000 quote on the React Partner Dashboard.

Upload & Route: The React frontend sends the image file to the Node.js/Express Server.

Microservice Handoff: Node.js temporarily holds the request and forwards the image to the Python/FastAPI Trust Engine.

Vision Validation: Python uses OpenCV to check the image's blur variance and brightness.

If Invalid (e.g., blurry): Python returns false. Node.js rejects the upload and tells the mechanic to retake it.

If Valid: Python returns true.

Storage & Ledger: Node.js uploads the image to Cloudinary, then saves the quote data and image URL into MongoDB.

Real-Time Alert: Node.js uses Socket.io to emit a proof_received event directly to the specific User’s React Native app.

Resolution: The User receives a push notification, views the image, and clicks "Approve." A final REST API call updates the MongoDB document status to APPROVED.

Workflow B: The "EV Slot Booking" (Zero Latency)
This flow demonstrates how you eliminate "Charge Anxiety."

Trigger: Driver opens the app. The React frontend opens a Socket.io connection to the Node.js server.

Initial State: Node.js queries MongoDB for nearby EV stations and sends the current availability (e.g., Charger A is Green/Available).

Action: Driver clicks "Reserve" on Charger A.

State Change: Node.js updates MongoDB, setting Charger A to BOOKED and starting a 15-minute expiration timer.

Global Broadcast: Node.js instantly emits a station_status_change event via Socket.io to every other user currently looking at the map. Charger A turns Yellow/Red on their screens without them refreshing the app.

Arrival: The driver arrives and clicks "Start Charging" (simulated via API), locking the slot.

